---
// Tick angles for the dial faces
const ticks = [-90, -45, 0, 45, 90];
---

<section class="panel section--band" id="science">
  <div class="container science">
    <div class="prose">
      <span class="eyebrow">The science</span>
      <h2>A normal yeast eats your oil. Your skin overreacts to the leftovers.</h2>
      <p class="summary">
        Everyone's skin hosts a yeast called <em>Malassezia</em>. It feeds on
        your skin's oil and leaves byproducts behind. Some people's skin
        overreacts to those leftovers. Mine does. That susceptibility is seb
        derm, and once I understood it, the fix became obvious. There are
        exactly two levers.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="dial-cards">
      <!-- Lever 1: lower the trigger -->
      <article class="dial-card">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 320 165" role="img" aria-label="Gauge turned down toward low">
          <g transform="translate(160, 130)">
            <path class="dial-track" d="M -100 0 A 100 100 0 0 1 100 0" />
            <path class="dial-fill dial-fill--down" d="M -100 0 A 100 100 0 0 1 -70.7 -70.7" />
            {ticks.map((a) => (
              <line
                class="dial-tick"
                x1={Math.sin((a * Math.PI) / 180) * 86}
                y1={-Math.cos((a * Math.PI) / 180) * 86}
                x2={Math.sin((a * Math.PI) / 180) * 100}
                y2={-Math.cos((a * Math.PI) / 180) * 100}
              />
            ))}
            <line class="dial-needle" x1="0" y1="0" x2="-49.5" y2="-49.5" />
            <circle class="dial-hub" cx="0" cy="0" r="10" />
            <text class="dial-minmax" x="-100" y="24">low</text>
            <text class="dial-minmax" x="100" y="24" text-anchor="end">high</text>
          </g>
        </svg>
        <span class="dial-card__tag">The trigger</span>
        <h3>Lower the trigger.</h3>
        <p>
          Knock the yeast down periodically with a gentle antifungal. Fewer
          byproducts, less to react to. This is the piece I was missing for
          years.
        </p>
      </article>

      <!-- Lever 2: raise the threshold -->
      <article class="dial-card">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 320 165" role="img" aria-label="Gauge turned up toward high">
          <g transform="translate(160, 130)">
            <path class="dial-track" d="M -100 0 A 100 100 0 0 1 100 0" />
            <path class="dial-fill dial-fill--up" d="M -100 0 A 100 100 0 0 1 70.7 -70.7" />
            {ticks.map((a) => (
              <line
                class="dial-tick"
                x1={Math.sin((a * Math.PI) / 180) * 86}
                y1={-Math.cos((a * Math.PI) / 180) * 86}
                x2={Math.sin((a * Math.PI) / 180) * 100}
                y2={-Math.cos((a * Math.PI) / 180) * 100}
              />
            ))}
            <line class="dial-needle" x1="0" y1="0" x2="49.5" y2="-49.5" />
            <circle class="dial-hub" cx="0" cy="0" r="10" />
            <text class="dial-minmax" x="-100" y="24">low</text>
            <text class="dial-minmax" x="100" y="24" text-anchor="end">high</text>
          </g>
        </svg>
        <span class="dial-card__tag">Your threshold</span>
        <h3>Raise your threshold.</h3>
        <p>
          Strengthen the skin barrier so it takes more provocation to flare.
          That's what a good moisturizer does.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>

    <details class="more">
      <summary>The full explanation</summary>
      <div class="more__body">
        <p>
          <em>Malassezia</em> is normal flora. It favors oily areas, feeds on
          the oil (sebum) your skin produces, and you cannot get rid of it. You
          wouldn't want to. It's supposed to be there.
        </p>
        <p>
          Seb derm is not an infection, and the amount of yeast isn't really
          the issue. Plenty of people carry the same yeast and never flake. The
          difference is you. Seb derm is a susceptibility. Some people's skin
          over-reacts to the byproducts the yeast leaves behind when it breaks
          down your skin's oil, especially certain free fatty acids like oleic
          acid. In susceptible people, those leftovers trigger inflammation,
          redness, and flaking.
        </p>
        <p>
          It isn't a classic allergy either. It's closer to an over-reactive
          inflammatory response, and three things tend to stack up in people
          who get it: a more reactive immune response to the yeast, a slightly
          more permeable skin barrier that lets irritants in, and active oil
          glands that keep the yeast well fed. That's why it hits the oily
          zones specifically, and why it flares with stress, poor sleep,
          illness, and cold dry weather.
        </p>
        <p>
          Neither lever is a cure, because your skin keeps making oil and the
          yeast keeps coming back. But together they keep the condition quiet
          with very little effort. Mine has stayed quiet for years this way.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .science { padding-block: 1rem; }
  .summary {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--color-ink-soft);
  }

  .dial-cards {
    display: grid;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    margin-block: 2rem;
  }
  .dial-card {
    background: var(--color-surface);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    padding: 2rem 1.75rem 1.75rem;
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-soft);
  }
  .dial-card svg {
    max-width: 260px;
    margin: 0 auto 1.25rem;
  }
  .dial-card__tag {
    display: block;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    color: var(--color-pop-deep);
    margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
  }
  .dial-card h3 {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    margin-bottom: 0.35em;
  }
  .dial-card p {
    margin-bottom: 0;
    color: var(--color-ink-soft);
  }

  .dial-track {
    fill: none;
    stroke: var(--color-line);
    stroke-width: 14;
    stroke-linecap: round;
  }
  .dial-fill {
    fill: none;
    stroke-width: 14;
    stroke-linecap: round;
  }
  .dial-fill--down { stroke: var(--color-accent); }
  .dial-fill--up { stroke: var(--color-pop); }
  .dial-tick { stroke: var(--color-ink-soft); stroke-width: 2; opacity: 0.4; }
  .dial-needle {
    stroke: var(--color-ink);
    stroke-width: 6;
    stroke-linecap: round;
  }
  .dial-hub { fill: var(--color-ink); }
  .dial-minmax {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 13px;
    fill: var(--color-ink-soft);
  }

  @media (min-width: 760px) {
    .dial-cards { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
  }
</style>
